  "meaning": " About: Barcroft Henry Thomas Boake (March 26, 1866 � found dead May 10, 1892) was an Australian poet.\n\r\nBorn in Sydney, Boake worked as a surveyor and a boundary rider in New South Wales and Queensland, but is best remembered for his poetry, a volume of which was published five years after his death. A sufferer of bipolar disorder, he is believed to have committed suicide. His body was found hanging by the neck eight days after he disappeared on May 2, 1892, from a stockwhip at Middle Harbour in Sydney. One writer on Boake's life has mentioned that the suicide took place during the 1891-93 depression when the poet was unable to find work, also noting that \"it has been suggested that he killed himself for the love of one of the McKeahnie girls,\" sisters of the horseman Charlie McKeahnie.",
